& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is a malignancy with variable biologic aggressiveness based on the tumor grade, presence or absence of vascular invasion, and pathologic and molecular classification. Knowledge and understanding of the prognostic implications of different pathologic and molecular phenotypes of HCC are emerging, with therapeutics that promise to provide improved outcomes in what otherwise remains a lethal cancer. Imaging has a central role in diagnosis of HCC. However, to date, the imaging algorithms do not incorporate prognostic features or subclassification of HCC according to its biologic aggressiveness. Emerging data suggest that some imaging features and further radiologic, pathologic, or radiologic-molecular phenotypes may allow prediction of the prognosis of patients with HCC.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>An invited commentary by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2021210151">Bashir</a> is available online.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210009">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210009">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="HCC with microvascular invasion (MVI) in a 63-year-old man with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. (A) Axial noncontrast T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows hyperintense foci (arrow) in a 70-mm lesion (∗), which is consistent with blood in the mass. (B) Axial arterial phase MR image shows enhancement greater than that of the liver, which is most pronounced in the periphery (arrowhead), representing rim arterial phase hyperenhancement (APHE). An ill-defined area of peritumoral enhancement (arrow) is seen in the adjacent parenchyma. (C) Axial hepatobiliary phase (HBP) MR image shows a nonsmooth tumor margin (arrow) and hypointensity in the lesion (arrowhead). The presence of one targetoid feature (rim APHE) results in classification of the lesion as LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific). (D) Photograph of gross pathologic specimens shows a lobulated margin (arrows) and internal hemorrhagic foci (arrowheads). (E) Photomicrograph shows tumor cells in a vessel (arrow), indicating MVI in a vessel (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig1.jpeg" height="2666" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. HCC with microvascular invasion (MVI) in a 63-year-old man with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. <b>(A)</b> Axial noncontrast T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows hyperintense foci (arrow) in a 70-mm lesion (∗), which is consistent with blood in the mass. <b>(B)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image shows enhancement greater than that of the liver, which is most pronounced in the periphery (arrowhead), representing rim arterial phase hyperenhancement (APHE). An ill-defined area of peritumoral enhancement (arrow) is seen in the adjacent parenchyma. <b>(C)</b> Axial hepatobiliary phase (HBP) MR image shows a nonsmooth tumor margin (arrow) and hypointensity in the lesion (arrowhead). The presence of one targetoid feature (rim APHE) results in classification of the lesion as LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific). <b>(D)</b> Photograph of gross pathologic specimens shows a lobulated margin (arrows) and internal hemorrhagic foci (arrowheads). <b>(E)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumor cells in a vessel (arrow), indicating MVI in a vessel (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows temporal development of histopathologic changes during hepatocarcinogenesis and their imaging correlates. The histopathologic changes are (left to right) a benign regenerative nodule in cirrhosis, a low-grade dysplastic nodule with increased morphologic atypia, a high-grade dysplastic nodule with increased morphologic atypia and a nuclear abnormality, an early HCC with thickening trabeculae, and a small progressed HCC with a thickened hepatic trabecula and small-cell change. The schematic images show progressive loss of visualization of the portal triads (ie, “loss of portal triads”), architectural distortion, fibrous bands, small-cell changes, and development of overt HCC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig2.jpeg" height="2088" width="2997" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustration shows temporal development of histopathologic changes during hepatocarcinogenesis and their imaging correlates. The histopathologic changes are (left to right) a benign regenerative nodule in cirrhosis, a low-grade dysplastic nodule with increased morphologic atypia, a high-grade dysplastic nodule with increased morphologic atypia and a nuclear abnormality, an early HCC with thickening trabeculae, and a small progressed HCC with a thickened hepatic trabecula and small-cell change. The schematic images show progressive loss of visualization of the portal triads (ie, “loss of portal triads”), architectural distortion, fibrous bands, small-cell changes, and development of overt HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="HCC in a 67-year-old patient with alcoholic cirrhosis. (A, B) Axial in-phase (A)and opposed-phase (B) gradient-echo T1-weighted images show a 25-mm mass (arrow) with signal intensity loss in B, greater than the signal intensity loss in the liver parenchyma (∗), representing more fat in the mass than in the liver. (C–G) Axial arterial phase (C), portal venous phase (D), T1-weighted (E), diffusion-weighted (F), and HBP (G) MR images show nonrim hyperenhancement (arrow in C), nonperipheral washout (arrow in D), an enhancing capsule (arrowhead in D), mild to moderate HBP hyperintensity (arrow in E), restricted diffusion (arrow in F), and HBP hypointensity (arrow in G). The mass met the criteria for LR-5 (definite HCC) and was treated with local-regional therapy without biopsy confirmation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig3.jpeg" height="3800" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. HCC in a 67-year-old patient with alcoholic cirrhosis. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial in-phase <b>(A)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(B)</b> gradient-echo T1-weighted images show a 25-mm mass (arrow) with signal intensity loss in <b>B</b>, greater than the signal intensity loss in the liver parenchyma (∗), representing more fat in the mass than in the liver. <b>(C–G)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(C)</b>, portal venous phase <b>(D),</b> T1-weighted <b>(E)</b>, diffusion-weighted <b>(F)</b>, and HBP <b>(G)</b> MR images show nonrim hyperenhancement (arrow in <b>C</b>), nonperipheral washout (arrow in <b>D</b>), an enhancing capsule (arrowhead in <b>D</b>), mild to moderate HBP hyperintensity (arrow in <b>E</b>), restricted diffusion (arrow in <b>F</b>), and HBP hypointensity (arrow in <b>G</b>). The mass met the criteria for LR-5 (definite HCC) and was treated with local-regional therapy without biopsy confirmation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Regenerative nodule in a 62-year-old woman with hepatitis C cirrhosis. (A) Axial HBP MR image shows a 10-mm mass (arrow) with uniform enhancement that is slightly greater than that of the background liver. (B) Photomicrograph shows a maplike pattern of OATP expression in the nodule (black ∗) similar to that in the background liver (white ∗). (OATP1B3 stain; original magnification, ×20.) The mass was categorized as LR-2 (probably benign). See Figure E2 for more images in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig4.jpeg" height="1278" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Regenerative nodule in a 62-year-old woman with hepatitis C cirrhosis. <b>(A)</b> Axial HBP MR image shows a 10-mm mass (arrow) with uniform enhancement that is slightly greater than that of the background liver. <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph shows a maplike pattern of OATP expression in the nodule (black ∗) similar to that in the background liver (white ∗). (OATP1B3 stain; original magnification, ×20.) The mass was categorized as LR-2 (probably benign). See Figure E2 for more images in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Low-grade dysplastic nodule in a 52-year-old woman with hepatitis C cirrhosis. (A, B) Axial arterial phase (A) and portal venous phase (B) contrast-enhanced MR images show an 18-mm mass (arrow) that is isointense (A) compared with the liver parenchyma and shows washout (B). The mass was categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). (C) Photograph of the gross pathologic specimen shows a nodule (arrow) that is distinctly larger than the rest of the nodules and of a color similar to that of the background nodules. See Figure E3 for more images in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig5.jpeg" height="1250" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Low-grade dysplastic nodule in a 52-year-old woman with hepatitis C cirrhosis. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(A)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced MR images show an 18-mm mass (arrow) that is isointense <b>(A)</b> compared with the liver parenchyma and shows washout <b>(B)</b>. The mass was categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). <b>(C)</b> Photograph of the gross pathologic specimen shows a nodule (arrow) that is distinctly larger than the rest of the nodules and of a color similar to that of the background nodules. See Figure E3 for more images in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="High-grade dysplastic nodule in a 71-year-old man with cryptogenic cirrhosis. (A, B) Arterial phase (A) and portal venous phase (B) contrast-enhanced MR images show a 9-mm nodule (arrow) that is isointense in comparison with the background liver during the arterial phase and shows washout during the portal venous phase. The nodule is categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). (C) Photograph of the gross pathologic specimen shows a nodule (arrow) that is distinctly larger than and of a color similar to that of the background nodules. See Figure E4 for more images in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig6.jpeg" height="1250" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. High-grade dysplastic nodule in a 71-year-old man with cryptogenic cirrhosis. <b>(A, B)</b> Arterial phase <b>(A)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced MR images show a 9-mm nodule (arrow) that is isointense in comparison with the background liver during the arterial phase and shows washout during the portal venous phase. The nodule is categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). <b>(C)</b> Photograph of the gross pathologic specimen shows a nodule (arrow) that is distinctly larger than and of a color similar to that of the background nodules. See Figure E4 for more images in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Early HCC in a 55-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. (A) HBP MR image shows a 12-mm nodule (arrow) that is hypointense compared with the background liver. (B) Photomicrograph of the pathologic specimen shows well-differentiated HCC, with invasion into the portal tract stroma. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) The approximate position of the limiting plate of the preexisting portal tract is outlined with the white dashed line. The bile duct is outlined in green, and a corresponding (paired) artery is nearby (∗). The portal veins are patent. Black arrows indicate small nests of stromal invasion by well-differentiated cells. The nodule is categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). See Figure E5 for more images in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig7.jpeg" height="1278" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Early HCC in a 55-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. <b>(A)</b> HBP MR image shows a 12-mm nodule (arrow) that is hypointense compared with the background liver. <b>(B)</b> Photomicrograph of the pathologic specimen shows well-differentiated HCC, with invasion into the portal tract stroma. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40.) The approximate position of the limiting plate of the preexisting portal tract is outlined with the white dashed line. The bile duct is outlined in green, and a corresponding (paired) artery is nearby (∗). The portal veins are patent. Black arrows indicate small nests of stromal invasion by well-differentiated cells. The nodule is categorized as LR-3 (intermediate probability of malignancy). See Figure E5 for more images in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Imaging features of progressed HCC. (A) Axial MR image shows a nodule-in-nodule appearance as an 18-mm nodule with a smaller internal nodule with APHE (arrow) and a larger background nodule without APHE (arrowhead). (B) Axial MR image shows a mosaic appearance, with a 43-mm nodule with multiple internal compartments with APHE (arrows) separated by fibrous septa (arrowheads). (C–E) Multifocal HCC with hemorrhage and necrosis. Axial noncontrast CT image (C) shows ill-defined hyperattenuating areas (arrowheads) in a confluent multifocal mass, which is typical of hemorrhage. Axial arterial phase (D) and portal venous phase (E)MR images show large areas of nonenhancement (arrows), which is typical of necrosis. Note that some nodules (arrowheads) are not necrotic and show nonrim APHE (D) and nonperipheral washout (E)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig8.jpeg" height="2525" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Imaging features of progressed HCC. <b>(A)</b> Axial MR image shows a nodule-in-nodule appearance as an 18-mm nodule with a smaller internal nodule with APHE (arrow) and a larger background nodule without APHE (arrowhead). <b>(B)</b> Axial MR image shows a mosaic appearance, with a 43-mm nodule with multiple internal compartments with APHE (arrows) separated by fibrous septa (arrowheads). <b>(C–E)</b> Multifocal HCC with hemorrhage and necrosis. Axial noncontrast CT image <b>(C)</b> shows ill-defined hyperattenuating areas (arrowheads) in a confluent multifocal mass, which is typical of hemorrhage. Axial arterial phase <b>(D)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(E)</b> MR images show large areas of nonenhancement (arrows), which is typical of necrosis. Note that some nodules (arrowheads) are not necrotic and show nonrim APHE <b>(D)</b> and nonperipheral washout <b>(E)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Satellite nodule in a 53-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 31-mm tumor (arrowhead) with nonrim hyperenhancement. Adjacent to the main tumor is a 9-mm satellite nodule (arrow). See Figure E6 for images of the satellite nodule."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig9.jpeg" height="1300" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Satellite nodule in a 53-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 31-mm tumor (arrowhead) with nonrim hyperenhancement. Adjacent to the main tumor is a 9-mm satellite nodule (arrow). See Figure E6 for images of the satellite nodule.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Infiltrative HCC with macrovascular invasion in a 58-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. Axial portal venous phase (A), T2-weighted (B), and diffusion-weighted (C) MR images show an ill-defined parenchymal mass (arrow) with T2 hyperintensity (A), restricted diffusion (B), and washout (C) and an enhancing mass with similar imaging characteristics (arrowhead) extending into the left portal vein, which represents tumor in vein. Note that the mass is most conspicuous on T2-weighted (B) and diffusion-weighted (C)images. Additional imaging features in this patient are shown in Figure E7. The mass was categorized as LR-TIV (definite tumor in vein)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig10.jpeg" height="1250" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Infiltrative HCC with macrovascular invasion in a 58-year-old man with hepatitis C cirrhosis. Axial portal venous phase <b>(A)</b>, T2-weighted <b>(B),</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(C)</b> MR images show an ill-defined parenchymal mass (arrow) with T2 hyperintensity <b>(A)</b>, restricted diffusion <b>(B),</b> and washout <b>(C)</b> and an enhancing mass with similar imaging characteristics (arrowhead) extending into the left portal vein, which represents tumor in vein. Note that the mass is most conspicuous on T2-weighted <b>(B)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(C)</b> images. Additional imaging features in this patient are shown in Figure E7. The mass was categorized as LR-TIV (definite tumor in vein).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="HCC with MVI in a 43-year-old man with hepatitis B cirrhosis. Arterial phase (A) and HBP (B) MR images show a 17-mm tumor (arrowhead) with nonrim APHE (A) and HBP hypointensity (B). There is peritumoral enhancement (long arrow in A) during the arterial phase, a nonsmooth tumor margin (short arrow in B), and peritumoral HBP hypointensity (long arrow in B). HCC with MVI was confirmed at resection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig11.jpeg" height="1238" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. HCC with MVI in a 43-year-old man with hepatitis B cirrhosis. Arterial phase <b>(A)</b> and HBP (<b>B</b>) MR images show a 17-mm tumor (arrowhead) with nonrim APHE <b>(A)</b> and HBP hypointensity <b>(B)</b>. There is peritumoral enhancement (long arrow in <b>A</b>) during the arterial phase, a nonsmooth tumor margin (short arrow in <b>B</b>), and peritumoral HBP hypointensity (long arrow in <b>B</b>). HCC with MVI was confirmed at resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Macrotrabecular HCC in a 25-year-old man with hepatitis B infection. (A) Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 130-mm tumor with nonrim hyperenhancement (∗), intratumoral arteries (long arrow), and peritumoral arterial hyperenhancement (short arrow). (B) Axial portal venous phase MR image shows nonperipheral washout (∗), a nonsmooth tumor margin (arrow), and satellite nodules (arrowheads). The tumor meets the criteria for LR-5 (definite HCC). (C) Photograph shows the dominant tumor (∗) with satellite nodules (arrowheads). A histologic slide is shown in Figure E9."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig12.jpeg" height="2433" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Macrotrabecular HCC in a 25-year-old man with hepatitis B infection. <b>(A)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 130-mm tumor with nonrim hyperenhancement (∗), intratumoral arteries (long arrow), and peritumoral arterial hyperenhancement (short arrow). <b>(B)</b> Axial portal venous phase MR image shows nonperipheral washout (∗), a nonsmooth tumor margin (arrow), and satellite nodules (arrowheads). The tumor meets the criteria for LR-5 (definite HCC). <b>(C)</b> Photograph shows the dominant tumor (∗) with satellite nodules (arrowheads). A histologic slide is shown in Figure E9.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Scirrhous HCC in a 53-year-old man with hepatitis B infection. (A, B) Arterial phase (A) and HBP (B) MR images show a 40-mm tumor with rim APHE (arrows in A), HBP hypointensity (long arrow in B), nonsmooth tumor margin (short arrow in B), and peritumoral HBP hypointensity (arrowhead in B). The presence of one targetoid feature (rim APHE) results in LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific) categorization. (C) Photograph of gross specimens shows a lobulated mass with tan-white areas reflecting the high content of collagenous connective tissue of scirrhous HCC. Additional radiologic and histologic features in this patient are shown in Figure E10."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig13.jpeg" height="2304" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Scirrhous HCC in a 53-year-old man with hepatitis B infection. <b>(A, B)</b> Arterial phase <b>(A)</b> and HBP (<b>B</b>) MR images show a 40-mm tumor with rim APHE (arrows in <b>A</b>), HBP hypointensity (long arrow in <b>B</b>), nonsmooth tumor margin (short arrow in <b>B</b>), and peritumoral HBP hypointensity (arrowhead in <b>B</b>). The presence of one targetoid feature (rim APHE) results in LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific) categorization. <b>(C)</b> Photograph of gross specimens shows a lobulated mass with tan-white areas reflecting the high content of collagenous connective tissue of scirrhous HCC. Additional radiologic and histologic features in this patient are shown in Figure E10.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="CK19-positive HCC in a 59-year-old man with cirrhosis. Arterial phase (A), portal venous phase (B), HBP (C), and diffusion-weighted (D) MR images show a 51-mm tumor with rim APHE (arrows in A), peritumoral APHE (arrowhead in A), and peripheral washout (arrow in B). The tumor shows targetoid HBP hypointensity, where the periphery (arrow in C) is more hypointense than the center (∗ in C), and a peritumoral HBP hypointense halo (arrowhead in C). The tumor also shows targetoid restricted diffusion, where the periphery (arrow in D) is more hyperintense than the center (∗ in D). The presence of targetoid features results in categorization of the tumor as LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific). See Figure E11 for histologic correlation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig14.jpeg" height="2499" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. CK19-positive HCC in a 59-year-old man with cirrhosis. Arterial phase <b>(A)</b>, portal venous phase <b>(B)</b>, HBP <b>(C)</b>, and diffusion-weighted <b>(D)</b> MR images show a 51-mm tumor with rim APHE (arrows in <b>A</b>), peritumoral APHE (arrowhead in <b>A</b>), and peripheral washout (arrow in <b>B</b>). The tumor shows targetoid HBP hypointensity, where the periphery (arrow in <b>C</b>) is more hypointense than the center (∗ in <b>C</b>), and a peritumoral HBP hypointense halo (arrowhead in <b>C</b>). The tumor also shows targetoid restricted diffusion, where the periphery (arrow in <b>D</b>) is more hyperintense than the center (∗ in <b>D</b>). The presence of targetoid features results in categorization of the tumor as LR-M (probably or definitely malignant, not HCC specific). See Figure E11 for histologic correlation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="β-catenin-mutated HCC in a 51-year-old woman with hepatitis B cirrhosis. (A) Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 27-mm tumor with nonrim hyperenhancement (arrow). (B) Axial HBP MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (arrow) and a nonenhancing capsule (arrowhead). (C) Photomicrograph shows largely retained normal membranous staining of tumor cells, but variably weak to strong (arrows) nuclear staining, indicating nuclear translocation of β-catenin. (β-catenin stain; original magnification, ×400.) (D) Photomicrograph shows that OATP expression in tumor cells is preserved (OATP stain; original magnification, ×400.) The tumor was categorized as LR-5 (definite HCC). See Figure E14 for more images in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig15.jpeg" height="2456" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. β-catenin-mutated HCC in a 51-year-old woman with hepatitis B cirrhosis. <b>(A)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image shows a 27-mm tumor with nonrim hyperenhancement (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Axial HBP MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (arrow) and a nonenhancing capsule (arrowhead). <b>(C)</b> Photomicrograph shows largely retained normal membranous staining of tumor cells, but variably weak to strong (arrows) nuclear staining, indicating nuclear translocation of β-catenin. (β-catenin stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(D)</b> Photomicrograph shows that OATP expression in tumor cells is preserved (OATP stain; original magnification, ×400.) The tumor was categorized as LR-5 (definite HCC). See Figure E14 for more images in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows radiopathologic phenotypes of HCC. This schematic is for conceptual purposes and does not include an exhaustive list of entities, nor does it capture all potential features or combinations. cHCC-CCA = combined HCC-cholangiocarcinoma, Enh = enhancing, Nonperiph = nonperipheral, TIV = tumor in vein."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig16.jpeg" height="2584" width="3796" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Illustration shows radiopathologic phenotypes of HCC. This schematic is for conceptual purposes and does not include an exhaustive list of entities, nor does it capture all potential features or combinations. <i>cHCC-CCA</i> = combined HCC-cholangiocarcinoma, <i>Enh</i> = enhancing, <i>Nonperiph</i> = nonperipheral, <i>TIV</i> = tumor in vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows features of proliferative and nonproliferative HCC. ADC = apparent diffusion coefficient, AKT = protein kinase B-1, AP = arterial phase, ARID1A = AT-rich interaction domain 1A, ATM = serine/threonine kinase, AXIN1 = axis inhibitor 1, CK19 =cytokeratin 19, CRP = C-reactive protein, CTNNB1 = β-catenin gene, EpCAM = epithelial cell adhesion molecule, FGF19 = fibroblast growth factor 19, GS = genomically stable, hyper = hyperintensity, hypo = hypointensity, IGF2 = insulinlike growth factor 2, iso = isointensity, JAK = Janus kinase, MAPK = mitogen-activated protein kinase, NOTCH = notch oncogene, Phospho-ERK = phosphorylation of extracellular signal-related kinase, Phosopho-S6 = phosphorylation of ribosomal protein S6, PI3K = phosphoinositide 3–kinase, RAS = Ras protein, RPS6KA3 = ribosomal protein S6 kinase A3, STAT = signal transducer and activator of transcription, TGF-β = transforming growth factor-β, TIV = tumor in vein, TP53 = tumor protein p53, TSC = tuberous sclerosis (1 and 2)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210009/asset/images/large/rg.2021210009.fig17.jpeg" height="4971" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Illustration shows features of proliferative and nonproliferative HCC. <i>ADC</i> = apparent diffusion coefficient, <i>AKT</i> = protein kinase B-1, <i>AP</i> = arterial phase, <i>ARID1A</i> = AT-rich interaction domain 1A, <i>ATM</i> = serine/threonine kinase, <i>AXIN1</i> = axis inhibitor 1, <i>CK19</i> = cytokeratin 19, <i>CRP</i> = C-reactive protein, <i>CTNNB1</i> = β-catenin gene, <i>EpCAM</i> = epithelial cell adhesion molecule, <i>FGF19</i> = fibroblast growth factor 19, <i>GS</i> = genomically stable, <i>hyper</i> = hyperintensity, <i>hypo</i> = hypointensity, <i>IGF2</i> = insulinlike growth factor 2, <i>iso</i> = isointensity, <i>JAK</i> = Janus kinase, <i>MAPK</i> = mitogen-activated protein kinase, <i>NOTCH</i> = notch oncogene, <i>Phospho-ERK</i> = phosphorylation of extracellular signal-related kinase, <i>Phosopho-S6</i> = phosphorylation of ribosomal protein S6, <i>PI3K</i> = phosphoinositide 3–kinase, <i>RAS</i> = Ras protein, <i>RPS6KA3</i> = ribosomal protein S6 kinase A3, <i>STAT</i> = signal transducer and activator of transcription, <i>TGF-β</i> = transforming growth factor-β, <i>TIV</i> = tumor in vein, <i>TP53</i> = tumor protein p53, <i>TSC</i> = tuberous sclerosis (1 and 2).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210009&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Erkan B, Meier J, Clark TJ, Kaplan J, Lambert JR, Chang S. Non-invasive diagnostic criteria of hepatocellular carcinoma: Comparison of diagnostic accuracy of updated LI-RADS with clinical practice guidelines of OPTN-UNOS, AASLD, NCCN, EASL-EORTC, and KLSCG-NCC. <em>PLoS One</em> 2019;14(12):e0226291.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0226291">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31821360/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Non-invasive+diagnostic+criteria+of+hepatocellular+carcinoma%3A+Comparison+of+diagnostic+accuracy+of+updated+LI-RADS+with+clinical+practice+guidelines+of+OPTN-UNOS%2C+AASLD%2C+NCCN%2C+EASL-EORTC%2C+and+KLSCG-NCC&amp;author=B+Erkan&amp;author=J+Meier&amp;author=TJ+Clark&amp;author=J+Kaplan&amp;author=JR+Lambert&amp;author=S+Chang&amp;publication_year=2019&amp;journal=PLoS+One&amp;pages=e0226291&amp;doi=10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0226291&amp;pmid=318213